{{bilateral|Australia–Netherlands|Australia|Netherlands}}
[[File:ABS-5368.0-InternationalTradeInGoodsServicesAustralia-MerchandiseExportsCountryCountryGroupsFobValue-Netherlands-A1829140T.svg|thumb|right|Monthly value of Australian merchandise exports to the Netherlands ([[Australian dollar|A$]] millions) since 1988]]
[[File:ABS-5439.0-InternationalMerchandiseImportsAustralia-CountryCountryGroupsCustomsValue-Netherlands-A1829456L.svg|thumb|right|Monthly value of Dutch merchandise exports to Australia ([[Australian dollar|A$]] millions) since 1988]]
'''Australia–Netherlands relations''' refer to bilateral relations between [[Australia]] and the [[Netherlands]]. Australia has an embassy in [[The Hague]]. The Netherlands has an embassy in [[Canberra]]. The two countries communicate and cooperate on a range of issues, including counterterrorism, climate change, human rights, and the [[Millennium Development Goals]].<ref name=DFAT>{{cite web|title=Netherlands country brief|url=http://www.dfat.gov.au/geo/netherlands/netherlands_country_brief.html|publisher=Department of  Foreign Affairs and Trade - Australian Government|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> In 2001 the countries signed an agreement on [[social security]] for those who have lived or worked in both countries.<ref name=DFAT/>

During the period 1606-1770, Dutch seafarers visited Australia numerous times.<ref name=HF>{{cite web|title=400 years of bilateral relations|url=http://www.hollandfocus.com/v2/index.php/community/netherlands/95-400years|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130624175026/http://www.hollandfocus.com/v2/index.php/community/netherlands/95-400years|dead-url=yes|archive-date=24 June 2013|publisher=Holland Focus|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>

At the moment, the Dutch Ambassador is Ms Annemieke Ruigrok.

During and immediately post the second world war, the [[Netherlands East Indies]] government in exile, was stationed in [[Wacol]], Queensland, and the [[Netherlands Indies Government Information Service]] in Melbourne, with the agreement of the then Labor Australian government. Australia was planned as the staging post for re-imposition of colonial rule in [[Indonesia]]. However, Australian maritime unions did much to frustrate this, with bans on manning/loading/coaling from September 1946 to a final ending of all bans in July 1949.<ref name=ba>Lockwood, R. (1975) Black Armada. Australasian Book Society Ltd., Sydney, Australia. {{Listed Invalid ISBN|9 09916 68 3}}</ref>

During the period 1947–1971 about 160,001 Dutch people emigrated to Australia, and {{as of|2006}} there are around 90,000 Australians of Dutch descent.<ref name=HF/>

Historically, diplomatic issues have arisen over [[West New Guinea]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Australia 'Won't Back' Dutch in Guinea Fight|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=A2RkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NXwNAAAAIBAJ&dq=australia%20netherlands&pg=5258%2C4658350|accessdate=19 June 2013|newspaper=The Calgary Herald|date=24 Jan 1962}}</ref> and [[Indonesia]]'s independence from the Netherlands (with Australia recognising the [[Indonesian Republic]] on 9 July 1947).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ismail|first=Sah-Hadiyatan|title=Australia and the Indonesian Independence|journal=Asian Social Science|date=May 2011|volume=7|issue=5|pages=151–157|url=http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/ass/article/view/7958|publisher=Canadian Center of Science and Education}}</ref> In 1955, Prime Minister [[Robert Menzies]] visited the Netherlands to discuss the issue of [[West Papua (region)|West Papua]] with Dutch officials including the Prime Minister of the Netherlands [[Willem Drees]] and Foreign Minister [[Joseph Luns]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.menziescollection.esrc.unimelb.edu.au/netherlands.html|title = Menzies on Tour: Netherlands|date = |accessdate = 18 December 2014|website = Menzies on Tour: Travelling with Robert Menzies, 1950-1959|publisher = eScholarship Research Centre, The University of Melbourne|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article91193629|title = Mr Menzies arrives in Amsterdam|last = |first = |date = 22 February 1955|work = |accessdate = 18 December 2014|newspaper = The Canberra Times|page = 1}}</ref>

