{{Culture of Chad}}
'''Chadian literature''' has suffered greatly from the turmoil which has engulfed [[Chad|the country]], [[Economy of Chad|economical]] and [[Politics of Chad|political]]. As with many cultures, literature in Chad began with [[Folklore|folk tales]] and [[legend]]s.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |title=Chadian Literature |url=http://www.tchad.org/research/literature.html |accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref> While [[French language|French]] is the dominant language, [[Arabic language|Arabic]] is also used by some Chadian writers. Chadian literature is more prevalent in [[France]] than in Chad itself, due to [[market demand]] and the repressive culture present in Chad.<ref>{{Citation |last=Abbink |first=Jon G. |title=Culture of Chad |url=http://www.everyculture.com/Bo-Co/Chad.html |accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref>

Chad's only literary critic, [[Ahmat Taboye]], wrote ''[[Anthologie de la littérature tchadienne]]'' in 2003 to spread knowledge of Chadian literature. Though there are not very many well-known Chadian writers, there are a few, including [[Joseph Brahim Seïd]], [[Baba Moustapha]], [[Antoine Bangui]] and [[Koulsy Lamko]].

