This article deals with the history and evolution of Sub-Saharans and Eastern Eurasians in Europe.
==DNA==
===Y-DNA===
In Europe, African Y-DNA chromosomes (which are defined as A, B and sub-Saharan variants of the Eurasian E) are consistently found at frequencies of less than 1% (with the exception of Portugal which may have up to 3% African Y-DNA).<ref>https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&lr=&cluster=11056732165607900434&um=1&ie=UTF-8&ei=F7DvSoyoMommNp2jwIoH&sa=X&oi=science_links&resnum=1&ct=sl-allversions&ved=0CAoQ0AIwAA</ref> It is a somewhat controversial issue over what an African Y-DNA [[haplogroup]] is, because some [[Eurasia]]n haplogroups such as haplogroup J, E3b, and even haplogroup R (particularly R1B) are often incorrectly labeled as being African because they can be consistently found at a high frequency in the Afro-Asiatic speakers that live in Africa.<ref>http://www.jogg.info/11/coffman.pdf</ref><ref>http://hpgl.stanford.edu/publications/AJHG_2002_v70_p1197-1214.pdf</ref> Genetic studies disprove this for example Haplogroup E3B has been proven by science to have begun in the Near East.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genographic.nationalgeographic.com/genographic/lan/en/atlas.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205224742/https://genographic.nationalgeographic.com/genographic/lan/en/atlas.html |archivedate=2011-02-05 |df= }}</ref>
===Mtdna===
African mtDNA (Haplogroup L which is genetically isolated) is rare in Europe although much more common than African Y-DNA.<ref>http://www.promega.com/Catalog/CountrySelect.aspx?returnurl=/geneticidproc/ussymp6proc/antti.htm</ref> It is most common in Portugal where 5% of people have it, though outside of Portugal it quite rare (consistently lower than 1%). For example, its frequencies run at 0.7% in Finland, 0.4% in Spain, and 0.1% in Ireland.<ref>Rhouda et al</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1852723 | pmid=17357081 | doi=10.1086/512822 | volume=80 | issue=4 | title=Mitochondrial DNA variation of modern Tuscans supports the near eastern origin of Etruscans |date=April 2007 | journal=American Journal of Human Genetics| pages=759–68}}</ref> As in Y-DNA many Caucasian mtDNA haplogroups (such as U6 and H1) and also some Eurasian mtDNA haplogroups such as (M1) are often wrongly described as African; probably because they can be found at high frequencies in the Afro-Eurasian speakers who also have a high consistency of Caucasian Y-DNA haplogroups.<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=1945034 | pmid=17620140 | doi=10.1186/1471-2164-8-223 | volume=8 | title=Mitochondrial lineage M1 traces an early human backflow to Africa | year=2007 | journal=BMC Genomics | pages=223}}</ref>
== History ==
=== Early history === The early history of Eastern Eurasian and African interactions with Europe can be found by the genetics of contemporary European populations. Both populations seem to have had little influence on Europe. Less than 1% of Europeans (including Spaniards) have African y-dna or mtDNA.<ref name="ReferenceA">Y-Chromosomal Diversity in Europe Is Clinal and Influenced Primarily by Geography, Rather than by Language</ref><ref>Determination genétique de l’individu Néolithique de Segudet (Ordino), les restes humains les plus anciens d’Andorre</ref><ref>Geographic Patterns of mtDNA Diversity in Europe</ref>
Eastern Eurasian dna is much more common and is represented mostly by the presence of haplogroup N3 in far north east Europe.<ref name="nature.com">http://www.nature.com/ejhg/journal/v15/n2/abs/5201748a.html</ref><ref name="nature.com"/> Many African populations have a large proportion of western Eurasian DNA particularly north Africa which is about 90% western Eurasian <ref>Worldwide human relationships inferred from genome-wide patterns of variation</ref> the above study is confirmed by y-dna and mtDNA analysis of north Africa for example over 90% of north African men belong to the western Eurasian E3B,J,G, or R1 haplogroups <ref name="ReferenceA"/> In sub-Saharan Africa amounts of western Eurasian DNA can be found in speakers of the afro-Asiatic language branch.
