'''Orbit spectrum''' is a [[spectrum]] that became available due to the placement of [[satellites]] into [[orbit]]. This spectrum, more also called the satellite spectrum, is a limited resource for every country. In order to ensure optimum utilization of orbit spectrum, the national administrations of countries worldwide undertake regular monitoring exercises. This orbit spectrum is used by service providers to implement satellite based [[satellite television|broadcasting]], [[telecommunication]] and [[meteorological]] services. To ensure quality of services, this orbit spectrum must be used by service providers as per terms and conditions approved by the respective Government. Regulatory measures must be enforced. This practice of regulating the spectrum within the limits of permissions or [[license]]s is part of spectrum management.

==Missions==
Orbit spectrum requires management which in turn needs effective spectrum monitoring exercises to enforce regulatory measures for ensuring legal usage of spectrum resource. Many examples of such spectrum monitoring exercises were undertaken by different [[countries]] around the world. 

===India===
One such initiative is Mission Orbit Spectrum by International Satellite Monitoring Earth Station (ISMES), [[Jalna, Maharashtra|Jalna]] Maharashtra. It was launched under the leadership of 'The Spectrum Man' Ajay Singhal, an IRRS officer and Head of ISMES Jalna since 19 February 2013. During this mission, ISMES exposed gross irregularities in the usage of satellite spectrum allocated to satellite service providers across the country. Approximately 60 cases of violation were uncovered during the first six months of 2014. 

Satellite spectrum usage is governed through specific technical and financial terms and conditions laid down in the licenses issued by the [[Indian government]], as per the provisions of  Indian Telegraphy Act 1885 and Indian Wireless Telegraphy Act 1933.

The orbit spectrum initiative by Ajay Singhal found a place in ''Limca Book of Records'' in January 2017. During this initiative, a low cost satellite spectrum monitoring facility was developed using a manual, steerable, dish antenna system named ''Small Wonder'' and software database named ''SAJAG''. The success of this initiative in highlighting the cases of violation in the usage of satellite spectrum and subsequent remedial actions taken by the satellite service providers was widely recognized.

