{{Infobox diocese |jurisdiction = Diocese |name = Kayanga |latin = Dioecesis Kayangana |country = Tanzania |metropolitan = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mwanza|Mwanza]] |rite = [[Latin Rite]] |cathedral = St. George, Karagwe |cocathedral = |area_km2 = |population = 675,476<ref name=tz>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Diocese of Kayanga | work = Tanzania Episcopal Conference | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.tec.or.tz/?page_id=358 | format = | doi = | accessdate = 19 April 2012}}</ref> |population_as_of = 2002 |catholics = 450,000<ref name=tz /> |catholics_percent= |bishop = [[Almachius Vincent Rweyongeza]] |coadjutor = |auxiliary_bishops= }}
The '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Kayanga''' ({{lang-la| Kayangana}}) is a [[diocese]] located in the city of [[Kayanga]] in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mwanza|Mwanza]] in Tanzania. It was established August 14, 2008 from territory previously in the [[Diocese of Rulenge]].
The diocese maintains 11 parishes, two schools, two hospitals and a health clinic. In addition to parish and administrative priests, three different communities of women religious minister in the diocese: the Religious Congregation of the Apostles of Unlimited Love Sisters (Masista Mitume wa Upendo Upeo), the [[Franciscan]] Sisters of St. Bernadette, and the Sisters of St. Therese of the Child Jesus.<ref name=tz />
==Leadership== * [[Bishop]]s of Kayanga (Roman rite) ** Bishop Almachius Vincent Rweyongeza (August 14, 2008 – present)
