'''Taokas''' ({{zh|c=道卡斯族|p=Dàokǎsī Zú}}) is one of a number of [[Taiwanese aborigines|indigenous ethno-linguistic groups]] that inhabited the plains of western [[Taiwan]]. The Taokas were located in the areas around today's [[Hsinchu City]]/[[Hsinchu County]], [[Miaoli County]], and [[Taichung City]] region. Several Taokas groups have been historically linked to many revolts that plagued Taiwan during the [[Qing]] era (1683–1895). The Taokas were not always opposed to Han encroachment on their lands as several Taokas groups were involved in building the [[Dajia District|Ta-Chia]] [[Mazu (goddess)|Mazu]] Temple. Today, only a small number of people in the central city of [[Puli, Nantou|Puli]] identify themselves as ethnic Taokas or even [[Taiwanese Aborigines]].
